               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e26100" n="162"> In Hebrew – שוה קריתים, as in Gen
                                14:5. It was suggested that this is Naveh in Transjordan. On such
                                designations see vol. 1, Introduction 3.2.6, p. 34.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e26104" n="163"> Known to us through his “signature” (achrosticon) in his
                                liturgical poems (piyutim), see Introduction
                                3.1.3.6.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e26124" n="164"> His writings were
                                found in the Cairo Geniza (no earlier than the 9th century). For the argument that he is
                                an earlier poet see Zulay, ibid. However, his
                                argument is entirely convincing.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e26144" n="165"> See above, n. 160.</note>
